        The first thing I notice is the light — not purple. I expected purple, saw it through the hull breach — but it's the quality of it, like stepping into perpetual twilight even though it's midday. Sunlight filters through the canopy overhead, turning lavender and soft, dreamlike. Everything glows.

        The second thing is the ground — soft. My boots sink slightly into a groundcover that feels like moss but isn't: purple-black and springy, almost pleasant underfoot. I take another step, then another — equipment bag heavy on my shoulder. The forest stretches ahead of me: tree trunks the width of ancient oaks but smooth and burgundy-dark. When I look up, the leaves are nearly black from below, but when the light catches them just right they glow deep violet.

        *Holy shit* — I'm on an alien planet.

        Buddy's voice bursts into my head —
        "Isn't this exciting, Kira! Let's talk about alien photosynthesis! You see, on Earth, plants use chlorophyll which absorbs red and blue light, but here the dominant photosynthetic pigment appears to—"

        I laugh despite everything — the pain in my leg, the dead pilots, the fact that I might die out here. Buddy wants to teach me about photosynthesis.

        I say —
        "Later, Buddy. Right now I just want to get to the water."

        Buddy replies —
        "Of course! Safety first! The stream is approximately eight hundred meters southwest. I'll guide you!"

        Southwest — right. I adjust my grip on the bag and start walking.

        ¶

        And that's when the quiet hits me.

        No birdsong. No insects buzzing. No rustle of small animals in the undergrowth. Just wind moving through the canopy — a soft, almost musical sound, deeper than Earth leaves, like the forest itself is breathing. My own footfalls become the loudest thing, muffled by the springy groundcover but still present. Still _very, very_ alone.

        I ask —
        "Buddy, you said no animal life detected, right?"

        Buddy —
        "Correct! The ecosystem appears entirely plant-based! Fascinating, really — on Earth, animals fill numerous ecological niches, but here it seems the plant life has adapted to—"

        I cut him off —
        "So it's just… quiet. No animals means no animal sounds."

        "Exactly! Though plant-based ecosystems can create their own acoustic environments through—"

        I tune him out, focusing on the silence. It's beautiful in a way — peaceful, but also wrong. Earth forests are never this quiet. There's always something: birds, insects, wind rattling dry leaves, water somewhere. Here there's just that soft breathing of thick leaves and my own footsteps.

        The forest floor is oddly clear, too. No undergrowth tangling my feet, no fallen branches to navigate around. Just the purple-black groundcover and those massive trees, spaced far enough apart that walking between them is easy. Almost like someone maintains it.

        That thought makes me uneasy, but I push it down.
