        I keep walking. The equipment bag digs into my shoulder. The air is thick—humid in a way that makes my skin feel damp, my hair already curling with moisture. It smells like growing things: sweet and earthy and floral all at once, with an edge of something unfamiliar underneath—not bad—just… other.

        The light shifts as I move deeper into the forest. Filtered through that purple canopy, everything takes on dreamlike lavender tones. Shadows aren't gray—they're purple-black, deep and soft. I pass a tree whose branches twist back toward the trunk in a way that makes my brain itch—wrong: the shapes are tree-like enough to be familiar but alien enough to remind me constantly: you're not home.

        Buddy, delighted —
        "Kira, I'm detecting some interesting atmospheric data! The oxygen-nitrogen ratio is remarkably similar to Earth, but there are trace elements that suggest—"

        I ask —
        "Buddy. Is the air safe to breathe?"

        Buddy, quick and cheerful —
        "Oh! Yes! Completely safe! Though the photosynthetic pigments I mentioned earlier create a unique light spectrum that—"

        I say —
        "Safe. Got it. Thanks."

        Our rhythm is getting better. Extract the useful information, let the rest go. Buddy means well. I'm learning to work with—

        Pain flares up my leg, sudden and sharp enough to stop me mid-step.

        I've been walking on adrenaline, ignoring the bandaged wound, focused on getting to water. But the injury doesn't care about my focus. I lean against the nearest tree trunk—smooth bark, faintly warm even in the shade—and try to breathe through it.

        The bandage is seeping. I can see it darkening through my pants. This is stupid. I'm injured, alone, should be resting not hiking through an alien forest. But water is eight hundred meters and I need it and the shuttle's life support is dying and—

        Buddy —
        "Kira, I'm detecting elevated pain signals! Your injury requires—"

        I say —
        "I'm fine. How much farther?"

        A pause. Then, quieter:
        Buddy —
        "Approximately six hundred meters remaining. Are you sure you can—"

        I say —
        "I'm sure."

        I push off the tree, test weight on my leg. It hurts. It's going to keep hurting. But I can walk.

        So I do.

        The limp is more pronounced now. Beauty doesn't make injury hurt less. Wonder doesn't erase the fact that I could die out here.

        I'm maybe fifty meters farther when I see it.

        Movement—high in the trees to my left, something shifting.

        I stop, heart suddenly pounding. I say —
        "Buddy, did you see that?"

        Buddy —
        "See what, Kira?"

        I point, even though Buddy doesn't have eyes.

        "Something moved. Up there."

        The forest is still again. Nothing but that soft wind-breath through the leaves.

        But I saw it. I'm sure I saw it.

        The quiet feels different now—not peaceful but charged, aware.

        ¶

        I'm not alone.

        Buddy, uncertainty creeping into his usually cheerful tone —
        "I'm not detecting any animal life forms, but in an unknown environment, sensors can miss—"

        There. Again. Higher up, something definitely moving among the branches.

        Plant life has to be—no fauna detected, Buddy said—but plants don't move like that—quick, purposeful, tracking—
